  "prompt": "How long do women spend shaving every week compared to the 50s?",
  "response": "The amount of time women spend shaving has likely increased since the 1950s due to changing beauty standards, increased availability of razors and shaving products, and the promotion of smooth, hairless skin as an ideal. Here\u2019s a comparison:\n\n### In the 1950s:\n- **Shaving Habits**: Shaving was less ubiquitous for women compared to today. Many women shaved only during warmer months or for specific occasions, focusing mainly on legs and underarms.\n- **Time Spent**: On average, women might have spent **5\u201310 minutes per session**, shaving a few times a week, totaling around **30\u201360 minutes per week**.\n\n### In the 2020s:\n- **Shaving Habits**: Women are encouraged to shave or remove hair more frequently and from more areas of the body (e.g., legs, underarms, bikini line, arms, etc.). The rise of grooming trends and social media has reinforced these expectations.\n- **Time Spent**: Women may spend **10\u201320 minutes per session**, shaving multiple times a week, totaling **1\u20132 hours per week** or more, depending on individual routines.\n\n### Key Differences:\n1. **Frequency**: Women today are more likely to shave daily or multiple times a week compared to the 1950s.\n2. **Areas Shaved**: Today, more body areas are targeted, increasing the time spent.\n3. **Cultural Expectations**: Beauty standards emphasizing hairlessness have become more pervasive, driven by media and advertising.\n\nOverall, women likely spend **significantly more time shaving today** than they did in the 1950s.",
